definition.value: A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the four carboxy groups of coproporphyrin I; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of uroporphyrin III; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of uroporphyrin I; major species at pH 7.3.

A partially-defined glycan in which the number and type of monosaccharides (hexose, pentose, etc.) is known, but the identities of the individual monosaccharides and the connectivity and configuration of the anomeric linkages are not known. See http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GNO_00000013.

A cyclic dicarboxylic anhydride that is oxane which carries oxo groups at positions 2 and 6. It is used as an intermediate in the production of pharmaceuticals, corrosion inhibitors, and polymers (E.g. epoxy polyesters).

A sulfated branched amino tetrasaccharide consisting of D-galactose at the reducing end with an alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->4)-[3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl moiety attached at the 3-position.

A sulfated branched amino pentasaccharide consisting of D-glucose at the reducing end with an alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->4)-[3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 4-position.

A sulfated linear amino tetrasaccharide consisting of D-glucose at the reducing end with a 3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl moiety attached at the 4-position.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of 11-oxomiltiradiene, arising from the deprotonation of the methylene group at position 14. Major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of (+)-pisiferic acid, arising from the deprotonation of the carboxy group. Major species at pH 7.3.
An abietane diterpenoid that is miltiradiene which carries a formyl group at position 20. It is a metabolite of miltiradiene.

A monohydroxybenzoic acid resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of ferulic acid with the amino group of 2-amino-5-hydroxybenzoic acid. It is an oat phytoalexin produced in response to pathogen attack and elicitation.
A phosphatidylinositol in which the inositol moiety is the 1D-myo isomer and the phosphatidyl group is located at its position 1.
An abietane diterpenoid that is miltiradiene in which the carbon at position 11 has been oxidised to the corresponding oxo group.
A plasmalogen of unkown fatty acid composition and where the glycerolipid is not defined, R3 can be H or a phospholipid.
A diacylglycerolipid where the fatty acyl at sn-1 has a saturated bond between carbons 1 and 2, the glycerolipid part is unkown, R3 can be an H or a phospholipid.
A member of the class of 2-pyranones that is tetrahydro-2H-pyran-2-one substituted by a pent-2-en-5-yl group at position 6. It is used as a flavouring agent and as an ingredient in perfumes.
A purine nucleoside in which guanine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.
A 6-(3-hexenyl)tetrahydro-2H-pyran-2-one in which the double bond adopts a trans-configuration.
A member of the class of 2-pyranones that is tetrahydro-2H-pyran-2-one substituted by a hex-3-en-1-yl group at position 6.

A partially-defined glycan in which the number and type of monosaccharides (hexose, pentose, etc.) and in which partial or complete stereochemistry of the monosaccharides is known, but the connectivity and configuration of the anomeric linkages are not known. See http://www.ontobee.org/ontology/GNO?iri=http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GNO_00000014.

A partially-defined glycan in which the identities of the monosaccharides that make up the glycan are known, but in which no linkage position or anomeric configuration is known. See http://www.ontobee.org/ontology/GNO?iri=http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GNO_00000015.

An amino oligosaccharide that is an undecasaccharide derivative consisting of a linear hexasaccharide chain of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, alpha-D-mannose, beta-D-mannose and two further N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues linked sequentially (1->4), (1->2), (1->3), (1->4) and (1->4), to the beta-D-mannose residue of which is also linked (1->6) a beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-[beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl branched pentasaccharide unit.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is succinic acid substituted by two methyl groups at positions 2 and 3 respectively.
A glycosyl glycoside comprising D-fructose attached to a D-fructofuranosyl residue via a beta-(2->1)-linkage.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2,3-dimethylpentane.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2,3-dimethylpentane.

A branched amino oligosaccharide comprising a linear trisaccharide of beta-D-mannose and two N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues all linked in sequence (1->4), to the mannosyl residue of which is (1->4)-linked an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue, together with an N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminyl-(2->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl tetrasaccharide unit linked (1->6) and an N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminyl-(2->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-[N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminyl-(2->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)]-alpha-D-mannosyl unit linked (1->3).
A sesterterpene that is produced by the heterologous expression of sesterterpene synthase EvQS from Aspergillus stellatus.
The 5-phosphonooxy derivative of L-lysine having erythro-stereochemistry.
A 3-penten-1-yne in which the double bond adopts a trans-configuration.
